WEBVTT

00:01.768 --> 00:04.669
<i>[jazzy music]</i>

00:04.737 --> 00:11.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:18.718 --> 00:20.752
[cheers and applause]

00:20.820 --> 00:22.387
<i>- From the Penn & Teller
Theater,</i>

00:22.455 --> 00:24.590
<i>at the Rio Hotel, in Las Vegas,</i>

00:24.657 --> 00:28.860
<i>here's our host,
Alyson Hannigan!</i>

00:28.862 --> 00:30.862
[cheers and applause]

00:30.864 --> 00:37.903
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:40.706 --> 00:42.274
- Welcome to "Fool Us."

00:42.341 --> 00:45.210
Get ready to marvel
at tonight's performers,

00:45.277 --> 00:47.779
because we've got
a fantastic four acts

00:47.847 --> 00:52.284
ready to try and fool our two
show-stopping superheroes.

00:52.351 --> 00:55.988
The Hulk and Ant Man
of magic--Penn and Teller!

00:56.890 --> 00:59.925
[cheers and applause]

01:12.905 --> 01:14.072
- You know the deal.

01:14.074 --> 01:15.974
If a magician fools
Penn and Teller,

01:16.042 --> 01:17.709
they win a "Fool Us" trophy.

01:17.777 --> 01:20.245
They also get to perform
in Penn & Teller's

01:20.247 --> 01:23.115
world-famous Magic Spectacular.

01:23.182 --> 01:26.418
Speaking of spectacular,
here is tonight's first act.

01:29.189 --> 01:31.656
<i>- When I do magic, it's more
than just doing</i>

01:31.724 --> 01:32.924
<i>a trick for someone.</i>

01:32.992 --> 01:35.026
<i>I want to absolutely fry
their brains,</i>

01:35.094 --> 01:37.296
<i>and it doesn't matter
how hard it is to do.</i>

01:37.964 --> 01:40.265
I was booked to do
a virtual show

01:40.267 --> 01:43.302
<i>for a client out in Colorado,
over video chat.</i>

01:43.903 --> 01:46.939
<i>So I thought, "What could I do
to really blow their minds?"</i>

01:47.006 --> 01:50.442
I live in North Carolina,
which is 1,500 miles away.

01:50.509 --> 01:53.278
<i>But I saw flights to Colorado
were pretty cheap that month,</i>

01:53.345 --> 01:56.515
<i>so I flew to Colorado,
and I hid an ace of spades</i>

01:56.582 --> 01:58.417
<i>just outside of their building.</i>

01:58.484 --> 01:59.885
<i>And I flew home that day,</i>

01:59.952 --> 02:02.654
and a month later,
I did the virtual show,

02:02.721 --> 02:04.289
and I kind of closed it
by saying,

02:04.291 --> 02:06.658
<i>"Wouldn't it be cool if I
could make an ace of spades</i>

02:06.725 --> 02:08.360
<i>appear hidden somewhere
there?"</i>

02:08.961 --> 02:11.597
<i>It's a story they're still
talking about, to this day.</i>

02:12.165 --> 02:14.432
And I grabbed one of these
magazines from the back.

02:14.434 --> 02:17.636
<i>In my show, I tend to not
use typical magic props.</i>

02:17.703 --> 02:20.972
<i>I try and borrow items from
the crowd, like their phone.</i>

02:20.974 --> 02:22.974
Their wallet
or just use something

02:22.976 --> 02:25.977
<i>that you might be able
to buy at a store nearby.</i>

02:26.045 --> 02:27.779
Penn and Teller,
I'm gonna try and fool you

02:27.781 --> 02:30.382
with something you may have
lying around your own home.

02:31.184 --> 02:34.152
[cheers and applause]

02:34.154 --> 02:36.321
- Enjoy the North Carolina

02:36.323 --> 02:39.324
comedy magic
of Hayden Childress!

02:39.391 --> 02:42.194
[cheers and applause]

02:42.261 --> 02:43.528
- Thank you.

02:43.530 --> 02:46.164
Penn, Teller, I want to
show you a piece of magic

02:46.166 --> 02:48.634
that I think
is gonna blow your minds.

02:51.237 --> 02:54.072
[blowing]

02:54.140 --> 02:55.807
Prepare to be fooled.

02:57.409 --> 02:59.678
Hmm.
[laughter]

03:01.881 --> 03:04.616
Okay. Pretty cool, but you
guys don't seem impressed.

03:04.684 --> 03:06.752
Probably because you think
I'm doing this,

03:07.853 --> 03:10.121
so I want to take it
to the next level.

03:10.123 --> 03:12.157
Alyson, would you mind
joining me here onstage?

03:12.224 --> 03:14.559
Give a round of applause
for Alyson, everyone.

03:14.627 --> 03:16.895
Alyson, I've brought
a roll of tape here.

03:16.897 --> 03:18.296
Would you mind
checking out the tape?

03:18.364 --> 03:21.499
Make sure the tape seems legit.
Like normal tape.

03:21.567 --> 03:22.701
- Yes.

03:22.703 --> 03:24.135
- And you can also check out
my fingers here.

03:24.203 --> 03:25.904
Make sure my fingers are normal,

03:25.971 --> 03:27.239
just in case Penn
and Teller think

03:27.306 --> 03:31.043
that maybe I used fake hands
for that first one.

03:31.110 --> 03:32.477
Everything seem good?
- Yeah.

03:32.544 --> 03:34.379
- All right. Everything good
with the tape, as well?

03:34.381 --> 03:35.780
- Yeah.
- All right. Cool.

03:35.848 --> 03:37.382
Only thing you need to know
about this kind of tape

03:37.449 --> 03:40.185
is it's industrial,
meaning it's super sticky.

03:40.220 --> 03:42.721
You can even feel that.
It's like maple syrup

03:42.788 --> 03:44.522
which, Penn,
I know you know a lot about.

03:44.524 --> 03:47.192
- I do.
- Check it out. My fingers.

03:47.194 --> 03:50.762
One roll of tape.
Taped together super tight.

03:50.829 --> 03:52.931
Alyson, can you give
that a couple wraparounds?

03:52.999 --> 03:55.400
Tape my fingers together
as tight as you can.

03:55.467 --> 03:58.003
- As tight as I can? Okay.
- Yeah. As tight as you can.

03:58.070 --> 04:00.472
You could even squeeze
my fingers more, if you want.

04:00.539 --> 04:03.675
- Okay. This seems bad
for your circulation.

04:03.742 --> 04:04.776
- Yeah.
I said a couple wraparounds,

04:04.843 --> 04:07.178
but this is, like, seven.
- Oh. Sorry.

04:07.180 --> 04:09.214
- No. It's all good.
It makes it more interesting.

04:09.216 --> 04:10.849
My fingers are even
changing colors, which...

04:10.916 --> 04:11.817
- Yeah. I'm...
- You can see there.

04:11.884 --> 04:12.818
It's like a second trick.

04:12.885 --> 04:14.386
- Concerned.

04:14.453 --> 04:16.121
- And so everything's
secure there?

04:16.188 --> 04:17.456
- Yes.

04:17.523 --> 04:21.493
- Alyson, I've brought
a metal ring. Check it out.

04:22.995 --> 04:25.564
One. Two.

04:27.100 --> 04:28.667
Alyson, I don't
do this on three,

04:28.734 --> 04:31.169
'cause I want you to be
surprised when it happens.

04:32.604 --> 04:35.874
- That's so cool.
- Thank you.

04:35.941 --> 04:38.677
And you see that ring
went right through my hands.

04:38.744 --> 04:41.146
- Yeah.
- We're gonna get it out.

04:41.914 --> 04:43.715
A lot of people think
the ring's gonna come out

04:43.782 --> 04:45.183
this way through the tape.

04:45.250 --> 04:47.819
It's actually gonna
come out this way.

04:51.790 --> 04:54.059
[all exclaim]

04:54.061 --> 04:55.694
- And Alyson, make sure,
one more time,

04:55.696 --> 04:57.062
my fingers are still together.

04:57.129 --> 04:58.963
It's still my fingers there.
The tape isn't broken?

04:59.031 --> 05:00.732
- No.

05:00.800 --> 05:02.467
- Thank you.

05:02.469 --> 05:04.469
Let's do it again.

05:04.537 --> 05:07.772
One. Two.

05:07.840 --> 05:10.175
[audience exclaims]
It goes right through.

05:10.242 --> 05:13.011
Now, this could be
some trick magic ring.

05:13.079 --> 05:15.013
After all, I brought it
out of my own pocket.

05:15.081 --> 05:17.215
- Right.
- Can I use your necklace?

05:17.850 --> 05:19.584
- Sure.
- I'm going to borrow it.

05:19.651 --> 05:21.820
And you are very magic,
so as far as we know,

05:21.887 --> 05:24.689
this isn't
a trick magic necklace, right?

05:24.691 --> 05:25.757
- No.
- Yeah. I know.

05:25.792 --> 05:27.492
I'm just yanking your chain.

05:28.828 --> 05:30.195
Okay.
Back to the trick. Thanks.

05:30.262 --> 05:31.396
- Okay.

05:31.464 --> 05:33.598
- If I put your necklace
on my hands like this,

05:34.633 --> 05:36.601
it kind of looks
like it went through.

05:36.668 --> 05:37.769
It's just for
the cameras though.

05:37.836 --> 05:38.937
See? It didn't really.

05:39.004 --> 05:41.540
But you'll see the moment
that it happens.

05:44.543 --> 05:46.178
[audience exclaims]

05:48.680 --> 05:50.515
- That's impressive.

05:50.583 --> 05:51.916
- You can see
that's your necklace.

05:51.984 --> 05:53.985
That ring.
Trapped in between my hands.

05:54.053 --> 05:56.988
Now, I can keep putting stuff
in my hands, over and over,

05:57.055 --> 06:00.191
but I want you to experience
this firsthand.

06:00.259 --> 06:02.527
Could you hold out your
left hand like this for me?

06:02.529 --> 06:04.262
- Yes.
- Yeah, and kind of do a

06:04.264 --> 06:06.231
A-okay. Perfect.
- Yeah.

06:06.298 --> 06:07.999
- You're gonna feel firsthand,
Alyson,

06:08.066 --> 06:10.668
how impossible it is
to pull your fingers apart.

06:10.670 --> 06:12.904
I'll avoid your fabulous
manicure, by the way.

06:12.971 --> 06:14.606
- Thanks.
- All right.

06:15.341 --> 06:17.342
This way, you can
experience firsthand that

06:17.344 --> 06:20.145
your fingers can't come apart.
Let Penn and Teller know.

06:20.147 --> 06:22.013
Is there any way
for your fingers to come apart?

06:22.015 --> 06:23.815
- No.

06:23.882 --> 06:25.917
- Penn, Teller, watch close.

06:25.919 --> 06:28.720
Alyson, it's about to get weird.

06:30.423 --> 06:32.824
Fingers forward.

06:32.826 --> 06:34.092
[imitates explosion]

06:34.159 --> 06:35.794
That's just
for hype and excitement.

06:37.362 --> 06:40.766
One. Two.

06:42.635 --> 06:44.302
[audience exclaims]

06:44.904 --> 06:47.172
Alyson, you're gonna see
that's my fingers

06:47.239 --> 06:50.175
and your fingers with the ring
with your necklace

06:50.242 --> 06:52.277
trapped in between us.

06:52.344 --> 06:54.312
- Oh, dear.
- Yeah. It's weird, right?

06:54.380 --> 06:55.780
- Yeah it is.

06:55.848 --> 06:57.516
- We're like one person
starting here connecting here.

06:58.217 --> 06:59.885
Who loves magic?
Alyson does.

07:00.752 --> 07:03.254
Yeah. I don't know about you,
but I'm having a blast.

07:03.256 --> 07:04.823
But obviously,

07:04.890 --> 07:07.759
I want to get this stuff
out of here, so Alyson...

07:07.826 --> 07:10.295
- Yeah?
- Try this.

07:10.362 --> 07:13.064
With your other hand
grab your necklace,

07:13.066 --> 07:15.333
and I want you to just
pull it out magically.

07:16.068 --> 07:18.036
[audience exclaims]
- Just like that.

07:18.103 --> 07:19.738
- What?

07:21.073 --> 07:23.274
- And you can feel the ring
on your finger.

07:23.276 --> 07:26.177
- Yes.
- We're gonna shake our hands.

07:26.245 --> 07:29.113
Just like this.

07:29.181 --> 07:30.081
We're just
gonna shake our hands...

07:30.149 --> 07:31.382
- Shake, shake, shake.

07:31.450 --> 07:32.750
- Like this. Shake. Shake.
Shake and bake.

07:32.752 --> 07:34.285
- Okay. Enough shaking.

07:34.287 --> 07:36.955
[audience exclaims]
- What?

07:37.022 --> 07:38.490
- Alyson, did you feel that?

07:38.557 --> 07:40.859
- No.
- I get that a lot.

07:40.926 --> 07:42.160
- Ew.

07:42.227 --> 07:44.229
- And you can see
we're still connected here.

07:44.231 --> 07:46.465
I take it that you're
right-handed, not left-handed?

07:46.499 --> 07:47.632
- Yes.

07:47.699 --> 07:49.000
- So we could stay
like this forever.

07:49.067 --> 07:50.835
- I have a lot of explaining
to do, but...

07:50.903 --> 07:52.303
- Yeah.
- Okay.

07:52.371 --> 07:54.339
- And you've got more TV work
to do, so I tell you what.

07:54.406 --> 07:55.574
We're gonna undo ourselves.

07:55.641 --> 07:57.976
- Okay.
- I won't cover it up.

07:57.978 --> 07:59.644
Watch our hands.

08:00.480 --> 08:03.682
[audience exclaims]
- Wow!

08:03.749 --> 08:06.618
Hayden Childress.
[cheers and applause]

08:06.685 --> 08:10.455
All right. Is it hard
to stand out, in magic?

08:11.323 --> 08:12.591
- Yeah. I'd say so.

08:12.658 --> 08:14.659
I mean it's really hard
to do something different.

08:14.661 --> 08:16.495
I don't know if you've ever
had your fingers taped.

08:16.529 --> 08:18.129
I hope I was the first one.

08:18.131 --> 08:20.098
- I mean not for a magic trick.
No.

08:21.133 --> 08:24.936
I've taped 'em during crafting,
but it's usually hot glue.

08:25.004 --> 08:25.970
- Okay. Gotcha.

08:26.038 --> 08:27.038
- Yeah.
- Gotcha.

08:27.105 --> 08:28.840
- What's your favorite audience?

08:28.907 --> 08:30.942
- I love the people
who buy tickets to see me,

08:30.944 --> 08:33.512
obviously,
'cause they come in liking me.

08:33.812 --> 08:36.514
- Aww.
- Although I do kind of

08:36.516 --> 08:38.283
like the crowds who are like,

08:38.350 --> 08:40.118
"Oh, my God.
There's a magician?"

08:40.185 --> 08:43.621
'Cause I love to exceed
their expectations,

08:43.623 --> 08:44.956
if that makes sense.
- Yeah, yeah.

08:45.023 --> 08:46.825
All right, Hayden.
Let's see if Penn and Teller

08:46.892 --> 08:48.893
know the secrets
to your tape trick.

08:48.961 --> 08:50.295
- All right.

08:50.297 --> 08:53.431
- Hayden, the very definition
of packs small-plays big.

08:54.533 --> 08:56.301
What a great routine.
- Thank you.

08:56.368 --> 08:58.503
- Every moment of it
is just beautiful.

08:58.570 --> 08:59.571
You've been doing that
for a while?

08:59.638 --> 09:01.072
It seems really well-tested.

09:01.139 --> 09:03.742
- Yeah. I've been doing it
for--oh, gosh.

09:04.443 --> 09:05.977
Since I was in high school
I think.

09:06.044 --> 09:07.512
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

09:07.580 --> 09:10.515
- It's really a modern version
of an ancient Japanese trick.

09:10.582 --> 09:14.118
You know, the thumb tie.
And it's just done beautifully.

09:14.186 --> 09:16.287
We have seen so many people
do thumb ties,

09:16.355 --> 09:18.022
and you bring
so much more to it.

09:18.090 --> 09:20.792
Probably the most
brilliant thing

09:20.859 --> 09:24.462
is using the spectator, Alyson,
to--

09:24.464 --> 09:26.831
In the same position
you're in, so she can feel

09:26.898 --> 09:28.533
how impossible it is

09:29.134 --> 09:31.402
to get that tape off
and actually feel that,

09:31.404 --> 09:33.671
which gets
a much stronger reaction.

09:33.673 --> 09:35.406
And I don't think
I've ever seen that before.

09:35.408 --> 09:37.342
Neither one of us
can remember seeing it.

09:37.409 --> 09:40.745
You know, people do that
with other people holding stuff

09:40.747 --> 09:42.814
and things like that,
but never with them

09:42.881 --> 09:45.417
in the exact same situation
you're in.

09:45.484 --> 09:47.919
And it's really, really good,

09:47.986 --> 09:51.789
and I also love that you start
with that stupid thing

09:51.857 --> 09:54.492
that everybody does to you
when you're a magician.

09:54.494 --> 09:57.428
"Hey, can you do this?"
And then we were kind of,

09:57.430 --> 09:59.263
"Okay great. You did it.
Have fun."

09:59.265 --> 10:02.600
And then having that tie in
with the whole plot

10:02.602 --> 10:04.102
of the whole thing
is really nice.

10:04.104 --> 10:08.206
I just love how simple
and clean--and I just--I know.

10:08.273 --> 10:10.609
We have a tip for you.
Just don't ever,

10:10.643 --> 10:12.710
ever take that out
of your routine.

10:12.778 --> 10:14.245
That is just a wonderful thing

10:14.313 --> 10:16.448
that you could be known
for, forever.

10:17.015 --> 10:20.785
- Hayden, does Penn's double
talk have meaning to you?

10:20.853 --> 10:22.754
- It does. I caught it.

10:22.821 --> 10:25.456
So thank you so much
for the compliments

10:25.458 --> 10:26.491
- Well, thank you.
It's wonderful. It's just--

10:26.558 --> 10:28.059
- So you didn't fool them?

10:28.126 --> 10:29.794
- No.
You know, but that's okay.

10:29.861 --> 10:32.397
I got to hold hands
with Alyson Hannigan.

10:32.464 --> 10:33.831
That was worth
the trip to Vegas.

10:33.899 --> 10:35.299
- Aww.
- Thank you so much.

10:35.367 --> 10:36.768
- All right.
- Wonderful.

10:36.835 --> 10:39.003
- Hayden Childress.
- Thank you.

10:39.071 --> 10:41.406
- Thank you.

10:41.473 --> 10:44.142
Coming up, more of
the world's greatest magicians

10:44.209 --> 10:47.011
try to fool Penn and Teller.
Stick around.

10:47.079 --> 10:48.379
[cheers and applause]

10:48.447 --> 10:51.282
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:54.486 --> 10:56.888
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:56.955 --> 10:59.624
[cheers and applause]

10:59.626 --> 11:01.159
- Welcome back to "Fool Us"

11:01.226 --> 11:03.995
where the impossible
is always possible,

11:04.062 --> 11:05.830
especially with our next act.

11:08.633 --> 11:11.703
<i>- So this is how I used magic
to make my family appear.</i>

11:11.770 --> 11:14.639
<i>I was at this party, and I met
this girl I wanted to impress.</i>

11:14.706 --> 11:17.375
<i>And I told her I'll help her
find the love of her life.</i>

11:17.443 --> 11:19.110
<i>I asked her
to take out her phone,</i>

11:19.112 --> 11:20.578
<i>open up the calculator,</i>

11:20.646 --> 11:23.048
<i>and punch in the number
of times she'd fallen in love.</i>

11:23.782 --> 11:25.383
<i>Multiply that
by the number of times</i>

11:25.385 --> 11:26.918
<i>you had your heart broken</i>

11:26.985 --> 11:28.953
<i>and the number
of boyfriends you had.</i>

11:29.020 --> 11:30.955
<i>Then multiply that
by any random number</i>

11:31.022 --> 11:32.924
<i>that only you know.</i>

11:32.991 --> 11:36.461
<i>I told her these are the odds
of you ever finding true love,</i>

11:36.528 --> 11:38.363
<i>but what if you call
that number?</i>

11:38.430 --> 11:40.398
<i>She did, and my phone rang.</i>

11:41.967 --> 11:44.869
We've been together ever since.

11:44.871 --> 11:46.404
<i>And now, we have a little baby,</i>

11:46.472 --> 11:49.407
<i>and he's my favorite thing
in the whole world.</i>

11:49.409 --> 11:51.776
<i>So now, I'm revisiting
all my favorite baby games.</i>

11:51.843 --> 11:52.744
Ooh, ahh!

11:52.811 --> 11:53.878
<i>We play peek-a-boo, of course.</i>

11:53.945 --> 11:55.413
Peek-a-boo!

11:55.480 --> 11:56.948
<i>But also games of chance,
like rock paper scissors.</i>

11:57.015 --> 11:59.584
<i>And amazingly, he wins more
than me,</i>

11:59.586 --> 12:01.152
which got me thinking.

12:01.219 --> 12:03.388
<i>I can combine these things
into some powerful magic.</i>

12:04.756 --> 12:07.125
I can't fool my baby
with tonight's trick,

12:07.192 --> 12:10.495
but maybe, just maybe
I can fool Penn and Teller.

12:11.129 --> 12:14.232
[cheers and applause]

12:14.234 --> 12:17.702
- Here to take on Penn
and Teller is Hans.

12:20.740 --> 12:23.941
- Thank you. This evening,
I'm going to influence you.

12:24.009 --> 12:26.477
I'm going to influence
what you think, what you say,

12:26.545 --> 12:27.512
and what you do.

12:27.579 --> 12:29.547
And that happens just every day.

12:29.614 --> 12:31.249
We all get
influenced by other people.

12:31.883 --> 12:34.786
The trick is doing it
without you noticing

12:34.853 --> 12:36.320
that you're being influenced.

12:36.388 --> 12:38.890
Penn, now, for this experiment,

12:38.957 --> 12:41.326
I have sent you some stuff
across the Atlantic.

12:41.393 --> 12:43.061
Can you open up that box, Penn?

12:43.128 --> 12:44.462
- Oh, yeah.

12:44.529 --> 12:45.596
Oh, my goodness.
- Whoa.

12:45.598 --> 12:47.432
- Okay. Penn,
what do you see in there?

12:48.634 --> 12:53.404
- I see a rock. Styrofoam.
