so I will write down
the result in advance,

14:04.509 --> 14:07.678
and Alyson, you're gonna get
the first choice here.

14:07.746 --> 14:11.616
Which two of you is
going to exchange items,

14:11.683 --> 14:12.717
in the first round?

14:12.784 --> 14:14.419
- I'm gonna trade with Penn.

14:15.053 --> 14:17.555
- You're gonna trade with Penn.
Okay. Trade with Penn.

14:19.091 --> 14:21.392
Ooh. That's heavier than
I thought it would be.

14:22.628 --> 14:26.664
- And my prediction says
Teller beats Penn.

14:26.731 --> 14:29.367
Teller's scissors
cuts Penn's paper.

14:30.535 --> 14:32.503
Now, for the second round,

14:32.571 --> 14:34.038
we're gonna do it
a bit more difficult,

14:34.105 --> 14:36.040
because now,
you can make two switches.

14:36.609 --> 14:40.077
I know exactly which two
switches you're going to make,

14:40.145 --> 14:42.580
so I'm going to write down
the results in advance.

14:43.381 --> 14:45.383
And I'm going to ask you, Penn,

14:45.450 --> 14:49.187
which two of you should make
the first switch?

14:50.522 --> 14:52.523
- Alyson and I.
- Alyson and you.

14:52.591 --> 14:54.558
Okay, switch with Alyson.

14:54.626 --> 14:57.328
- I just thought she was
getting tired holding the rock.

14:57.330 --> 14:59.330
- Yeah. Good idea.

14:59.397 --> 15:01.565
Teller, can you just
point two of you?

15:01.633 --> 15:03.167
Could you do the second switch?

15:06.005 --> 15:07.272
- Thank you.
- You switched with Alyson,

15:08.273 --> 15:12.476
and my prediction says
Alyson beats Teller.

15:12.544 --> 15:16.547
Alyson's scissors cuts Teller's
paper, and Penn beats Alyson.

15:17.249 --> 15:19.250
Penn's rock crushes
Alyson's scissors.

15:20.218 --> 15:21.386
- Wow.

15:21.453 --> 15:23.488
- Thank you.
That's what I was hoping for.

15:25.824 --> 15:27.758
And for the final round,
this is the most difficult one,

15:27.760 --> 15:30.861
because now you can make
three switches.

15:30.929 --> 15:32.363
And now,
you can try to outsmart me.

15:32.430 --> 15:35.133
For example, Penn and Teller,
if you do the first switch,

15:35.767 --> 15:37.735
for the second switch,
you can switch back again.

15:37.802 --> 15:39.203
And for the third switch,

15:39.270 --> 15:41.372
well, you can do
the same switch three times,

15:41.374 --> 15:43.040
or you can do two
different switches,

15:43.108 --> 15:46.277
or you can do
all three different switches.

15:46.345 --> 15:49.447
Whatever you think would be the
hardest for me to anticipate.

15:50.515 --> 15:52.817
And Alyson, not to put
any pressure on you,

15:52.884 --> 15:55.486
but women who are considered
very smart

15:55.553 --> 15:59.090
and very beautiful--they tend
to choose scissors over rock,

15:59.157 --> 16:02.360
in about 65% of the times.
- Wow.

16:02.427 --> 16:05.330
- Not trying to influence you
in any way, of course. Or am I?

16:06.065 --> 16:08.967
But Alyson, which two of you
should make the first switch?

16:11.002 --> 16:12.937
- Penn and Teller should switch.

16:13.004 --> 16:14.739
- Penn and Teller
do the first switch.

16:15.440 --> 16:18.543
And Penn, which two of you
should make the second switch?

16:19.611 --> 16:23.214
- I like having the rock.
Me and Teller.

16:24.116 --> 16:26.617
- And Teller, can you point
to two of you

16:26.619 --> 16:28.319
who should do the last switch?

16:31.289 --> 16:32.957
You'll switch with Penn.
Okay. Switch.

16:34.893 --> 16:39.163
Now, exactly as I thought,
and that is why

16:39.231 --> 16:42.000
there is nothing written
on this notepad,

16:42.667 --> 16:45.570
because I told you
I was gonna take a huge risk,

16:45.637 --> 16:47.171
and I did that
a couple of weeks ago

16:47.173 --> 16:51.108
when I sent you those items.
And today, I took another risk.

16:51.176 --> 16:52.910
The risk that none of you
would have that idea

16:52.978 --> 16:55.446
to look down
at that piece of paper

16:55.514 --> 16:57.548
that you have been passing
amongst you,

16:57.615 --> 16:59.250
because if you did,

17:00.419 --> 17:02.520
you could have done
one switch differently,

17:03.721 --> 17:06.124
and all my predictions
would be wrong.

17:06.191 --> 17:08.259
Penn, you figured out
what to do already.

17:08.261 --> 17:10.094
Open up and read
just the first line.

17:12.264 --> 17:13.831
What does the first line said?

17:15.534 --> 17:19.037
- Teller beats Alyson.
That's true. Penn--

17:19.071 --> 17:20.938
- Teller's rock. Yes.

17:20.940 --> 17:23.808
- Penn beats Teller.
Which is true.

17:23.875 --> 17:24.942
- Penn's--yes.

17:25.010 --> 17:27.445
- And Alyson beats Penn
which is true.

17:29.514 --> 17:30.782
- Thank you very much.

17:30.849 --> 17:33.284
- Wow.

17:33.351 --> 17:35.053
That's amazing.

17:37.222 --> 17:39.123
Hans!

17:41.226 --> 17:43.327
- Thank you, Alyson.
- That is so impressive.

17:43.394 --> 17:46.297
Were you, like,
the most annoying person

17:46.299 --> 17:49.533
to play paper rock scissors
with on the schoolyard?

17:49.535 --> 17:51.002
- I was probably
the richest one,

17:51.069 --> 17:53.071
because we would play for money.

17:53.105 --> 17:54.505
- Ooh, nice.

17:54.572 --> 17:56.774
Are there
many magicians in Norway?

17:56.841 --> 17:59.076
- Well, not many, but now,
we have a magic club,

17:59.078 --> 18:01.579
and last week,
I was elected president.

18:01.646 --> 18:05.516
It was kind of awkward though,
since I got both of the votes.

18:05.584 --> 18:07.351
The other guy knew
I voted for myself.

18:07.418 --> 18:09.787
- [laughs]

18:09.855 --> 18:11.222
Okay, Hans.

18:11.289 --> 18:15.126
Let's see if you won our game
of rock paper trophy.

18:17.096 --> 18:19.931
- Well, you certainly
blew our minds.

18:19.998 --> 18:23.000
We were just flabbergasted
right away.

18:23.068 --> 18:25.736
It's a beautiful trick.
I have been--what has it been?

18:25.803 --> 18:28.539
Like five years now.
I've been bringing up to Teller

18:28.606 --> 18:30.808
I want to do
a rock paper scissors trick.

18:30.875 --> 18:33.777
I loved it so much.
I love how simple it is.

18:33.845 --> 18:35.279
What a great game it is.

18:35.347 --> 18:37.014
I love the props being sent.

18:37.082 --> 18:40.151
I love the giant rock.
The giant scissors.

18:40.218 --> 18:42.286
The giant paper.

18:42.353 --> 18:44.221
I loved everything about this,

18:44.223 --> 18:46.624
and you're just
a great performer.

18:46.626 --> 18:49.427
The style was very clean,
turning it around.

18:49.494 --> 18:53.531
I loved it, but I do not think
you fooled us,

18:53.598 --> 18:57.301
because the way
this went seems inevitable.

18:57.303 --> 18:59.937
It seems like it's the only way
it could go.

19:00.004 --> 19:03.174
This is the only punchline
you could have,

19:03.241 --> 19:05.809
but as we know, in magic,

19:05.877 --> 19:07.445
you can always make it look

19:07.512 --> 19:10.147
like what happened
is what you wanted,

19:10.215 --> 19:11.715
even when it's not
what you wanted.

19:11.717 --> 19:13.985
So we think you didn't fool us,

19:14.052 --> 19:16.887
'cause you were using
multiple outs.

19:16.955 --> 19:19.557
You had a different way
to make everything okay,

19:19.624 --> 19:20.891
no matter what we did.

19:20.959 --> 19:22.393
- Is that right, Hans?

19:22.395 --> 19:23.661
- Does that mean, for example,

19:23.728 --> 19:25.863
you think that,
if something else happened,

19:25.931 --> 19:27.698
well maybe something
was written on the next page...

19:27.765 --> 19:28.799
- Yeah. Yeah.
- Of the notepad?

19:28.801 --> 19:30.134
- Something like that.
- So that--

19:30.202 --> 19:31.702
- A different page,
or maybe there is some answer

19:31.769 --> 19:33.971
in the box,
or something like that,

19:34.038 --> 19:36.274
and it seems inevitable,
but it really wasn't.

19:36.341 --> 19:37.909
- The outcome is what you saw.

19:37.976 --> 19:39.410
They are exactly
the same each time.

19:39.477 --> 19:41.812
There absolutely no multiple
outcomes,

19:41.879 --> 19:44.949
so I would say just-- [laughter]

19:48.353 --> 19:51.021
- Uh, yeah.

19:51.089 --> 19:52.756
Hans beats Penn.

19:52.824 --> 19:55.426
Hans beats Teller.
Hans wins the game.

19:55.493 --> 20:00.097
[cheers and applause]
- Yay! Hans, you fooled them.

20:00.164 --> 20:01.632
- We're gonna come up
and shake your hand.

20:01.700 --> 20:04.135
- Ohh.

20:04.202 --> 20:06.537
Oh, Hans.
- That's amazing.

20:06.604 --> 20:09.773
- Okay. We have a Fooler.

20:09.775 --> 20:12.643
- So beautiful.

20:12.710 --> 20:15.780
- Hans, that's awesome.
- Thank you guys.

20:15.847 --> 20:18.148
Thank you guys, except for
getting a little baby,

20:18.216 --> 20:21.652
this is the biggest thing
that happen to me.

20:21.720 --> 20:23.821
- So great, Hans. So great.

20:25.224 --> 20:31.996
- Congratulations, Hans!

20:32.063 --> 20:33.797
And we have a winner.

20:33.799 --> 20:35.766
Penn and Teller just added
an act

20:35.833 --> 20:37.735
to their Vegas magic show.

20:37.802 --> 20:40.037
Is there room
for one more on the bill?

20:40.104 --> 20:42.439
Find out when "Fool Us" returns.

20:42.507 --> 20:46.244
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:49.981 --> 20:54.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:54.953 --> 20:58.722
- Welcome back. We've seen Penn
and Teller get fooled once,

20:58.790 --> 21:00.991
but could this be
a two-Fooler night?

21:01.059 --> 21:03.794
Let's meet our next contender
and find out.

21:06.164 --> 21:09.267
- I'm Benjamin Barnes,
and my greatest power

21:09.301 --> 21:12.670
is turning "nos"
into "yeses."

